column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON ROUTE 113 AT MARYLAND ROUTE 12 IN SNOW HILL, MARYLAND, THE MAHOGANY COMPANY VEHICLE REAR ENDED ANOTHER VEHICLE RESULTING IN A TRACTOR FIRE FOR THE MAHOGANY COMPANY TRACTOR AND A SPILL INSIDE THE MAHOGANY COMPANY TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT. MARCOR ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. OF SALISBURY, MARYLAND WAS CONTRACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER, MARCOR ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. DETERMINED THE RELEASE CAME FROM TWO CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR ONE GALLON PLASTIC RECEPTACLES.  EACH CARTON WAS GOING TO BE DELIVERED TO A DIFFERENT CONSIGNEE, MARCOR ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. USED ABSORBENT RAGS AND TYVEK SUITS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  MARCOR ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. PLACED THE IMPACTED CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTONS, AND EIGHT DAMAGED PLASTIC RECEPTACLES INTO FOUR, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  MARCOR ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE FOUR, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS.  ONE INJURY WAS REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  THE MAHOGANY COMPANY DRIVER WAS SENT TO PENINSULA REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER FOR EXAMINATION, TREATMENT, AND WAS RELEASED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A CONTAINMENT TANK.  ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES OF FORT WAYNE, IN WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND FOR CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY SIX GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO SOME CONCRETE AND INTO THE CONTAINMENT TANK.  ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC. PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED DRUM WERE PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM WHICH WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

IT WAS DISCOVERED, UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, THAT ONE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM CONTAINING WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY FORTY-FIVE GALLONS WHILE EN ROUTE BETWEEN WICHITA FALLS, TEXAS AND THE DENTON, TEXAS DISTRIBUTION CENTER.  THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER WHILE EN ROUTE AND IS SUSPECTED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAYS OF STATE HIGHWAY 287 AND STATE HIGHWAY 380 IN TEXAS.  A MANAGEMENT INVESTIGATION IS CURRENTLY UNDERWAY TO UNDERSTAND THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND TO EDUCATE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HANDLERS AND WORKERS ON THE PROPER PRE-TRANSPORTATION, TRANSPORTATION, AND UNLOADING PRACTICES TO AVOID SIMILAR OCCURRENCES IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 5, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM MARK WEST HYDROCARBON.  THEY TOLD ME THAT THE STORAGE TANK AT THE ROUT 50 SATELLITE PLANT HAD STARTED LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, AND THAT I WAS NEEDED THERE AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.  I LEFT THE OFFICE AS SOON AS I HUNG THE PHONE UP.  WHEN I GOT TO THE PLANT, THE HILLSBORO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALREADY THERE.  JAMES HALL, A DRIVER FOR L&L TRANSPORTATION WAS ALSO AT THE PLANT.  JAMES TOLD ME THAT HE WAS UNLOADING HIS TANK TRUCK INTO THE STORAGE TANK, AND WHEN HE WAS ALMOST FINISHED, HE HEARD A NOISE COME FROM THE TANK. HE LOOKED OVER AT THE STORAGE TANK AND FOUND THAT THE TANK HAD STARTED LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM.  AT THIS POINT JAMES SHUT HIS TRUCK DOWN AND CLOSED ALL THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVES AT THE PLANT.  I TOOK A GOOD LOOK AT THE LEAK AND DETERMINED THAT IT COULD NOT BE REPAIRED WITHOUT HELP.  AT THIS POINT I CALLED ED MILLER AT OUR FLORANCE OFFICE, WHO IS OVER OUR SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  I TOLD HIM WHAT WAS GOING ON, AND HE TOLD ME HE WOULD GET SOME HELP TO US.  WITHIN A FEW MINUTES, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM RON CRIST, TELLING ME THAT HE WAS ON HIS WAY.  I ALSO RECEIVED A CALL FROM TOM WRIGHT WHO ASKED WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS AND WHAT HE COULD DO TO HELP.  I THEN RECEIVED A CALL FROM JEFF VANDEMARK WITH INDUSTRIAL PROPANE SERVICE.  HE ASKED WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS, AND TOLD ME HE WAS SENDING TWO PEOPLE TO HELP AND IT WOULD TAKE FIVE OR SIX HOURS FOR THEM TO GET THERE.  BY THIS TIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS BAD ENOUGH THAT THEY SHOULD SHUT DOWN STATE ROUTE 50.  WE DETERMINED THAT THE 76% OF LIQUID PROPANE IN THE STORAGE TANK HAD TO BE REMOVED.  BEFORE RON CRIST ARRIVED, HE CALLED AGAIN TO LET US KNOW THAT IF WE WRAPPED WET TOWELS AROUND THE INTERNAL VALVE, THIS MIGHT SLOW OR EVEN STOP THE LEAK.  THE HIGHLAND COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM TOOK ON THE JOB OF WRAPPING THE WET RAGS AROUND THE VALVE AND THIS DID HELP SLOW THE LEAK.  L&L TRANSPORTATION DID NOT WANT THEIR TRANSPORT TRUCK CLOSE TO THE STORAGE TANK, WHERE IT NEEDED TO BE IN ORDER TO PUMP THE GAS BACK OUT.  SO I CALLED ONE OF OUR BOBTAILS TO THE SITE SO WE COULD USE IT TO TAKE GAS FROM THE STORAGE TANK AND PUT BACK INTO THE TRANSPORT.  AFTER STARTING THIS PROCESS, RON CRIST MADE A FEW CALLS AND BEFORE LONG, WE HAD SEVERAL BOBTAILS FROM OUR BRANCH AND OTHER BRANCHES TO HELP EVACUATE THE 30,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK.  BEFORE THE TANK WAS EMPTY, JERRY DAVIS AND JEREMY VIK FROM IPS ARRIVED AT THE PLANT.  SOON AFTER THE STORAGE TANK WAS EMPTY OF LIQUID., JERRY STARTED THE PROCESS OF BURNING THE VAPOR PRESSURE FROM THE STORAGE TANK.  AROUND 9:30 PM THE VAPOR PRESSURE WAS DOWN TO NOTHING AND EVERYONE LEFT THE PLANT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OPENED STATE ROUT 50 AROUND 7:30 PM.  THE NEXT MORNING, IPS ARRIVED AT THE PLANT AND TOOK THE PIPING APART AND REMOVED THE INTERNAL VALVE FROM THE STORAGE TANK.  THEY FOUND A CRACK IN THE BODY OF THE VALVE, WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK.  THEY REPLACED THE VALVE, AND ADDED A PIECE OF FLEX HOSE IN THE PIP
PAIL WAS PUNCTURED ON THE DOCK BY DOCKWORKER

column168: THE DRIVER HAD THE UNLOADING HOSE HOOKED TO THE TRAILER AND LYING UP ON THE CONTAINMENT AREA WALL.  BEFORE CONNECTING TO THE CUSTOMER LINE, HE STARTED TO PRESSURIZE THE TRAILER.  THE AIR-OPERATED EMERGENCY VALVE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS OPEN AND THE PRODUCT BEGAN FLOW OUT OF THE HOSE.  THE INVESTIGATION INTO WHY THE VALVE WAS OPEN WAS INCONCLUSIVE.  THE DRIVER SAID THE VALVE WAS FAULTY, BUT WE WERE NOT ABLE TO FIND A PROBLEM WITH THE VALVE.  IT WAS REMOVED, INSPECTED, AND TESTED OK.  WE BELIEVE THE VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN AT THE LOADING SITE, WHERE THE PRODUCT IS LOADED THROUGH THE UNLOADING HOSE, AND THE DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK IT.  WE ARE, HOWEVER CONTINUING TO LOOK INTO AS TO WHY THE EMERGENCY SHUT-DOWN SYSTEM DID NOT OPERATE/CLOSE THE VALVE IN A TIMELY MANNER.  THIS CONTRIBUTED TO THE SEVERITY OF THE SPILL.  REMIND DRIVERS TO NEVER START PRESSURIZING THEIR CARGO TANKS BEFORE MAKING THE CONNECTION.  REFRESHER TRAINING TO DRIVERS ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  DRIVER WAS TERMINATED BUT HAD GRIEVED HIS TERMINATION.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL OF THE TRAILER, EMPLOYEES BEGAN UNLOADING THE CONTAINERS.  ONE CONTAINER HAD TIPPED OVER DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE CONTAINER HAD OPENED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER.  THE EMPLOYEES, IN THEIR PROPER PPE (PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT) GLOVES, SAFETY SHOES, SAFETY GLASSES AND COMPANY UNIFORM SWEPT UP THE TRAILER UTILIZING BROOMS AND SHOVELS, THEN PROCEEDED TO SANITIZE THE TRAILER WITH CLEANING SOLUTION.  NO INJURIES OCCURRED FROM THIS INCIDENT.  THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED AND EDUCATED REGARDING THE PACKAGING GUIDELINES AND HAVE OFFERED TO DEMONSTRATE PROPER PACKAGING OF SHARPS AND REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE.

INCIDENT OCCURRED ON NOVEMBER 12, 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 AM.  DRIVER HAD TO APPLY EXTREME BRAKES WHEN HE WAS CUT OFF BY A VEHICLE ON THE INTERSTATE NEAR DETROIT MICHIGAN.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE FIRST STOP AND CONTACTED FREIGHT MANAGEMENT WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION. HE EXPLAINED THE INCIDENT TO MGMT AND ALSO SAID THAT HE FELT THE LOAD SHIFT AND NOTICED A TOTE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  THE DRIVER DID NOT CLIMB INTO THE TRUCK TO ASSESS THE EXTENT OF DAMAGE (ACTION#1).  THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO THE NEXT STOP AND AFTER APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES WHILE DRIVING THE DRIVER OBSERVED MATERIAL STARTED TO LEAK OUT OF THE TRUCK.  HE STOPPED THE VEHICLE ON GREENFIELD BLVD AND CHECKED THE TRAILER.  MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER BUT HE WAS NOT POSITIVE WHICH PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER AND THE MATERIAL CLOSE TO THE TRUCK WERE CONTAINED USING THE 5 GALLON SPILL ABSORBENT PADS AND SOCKS.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED MGMT ABOUT THE SITUATION AND CALLED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  PALM MGMT ACQUIRED BOL FROM SHIPPING DEPARTMENT AND NOTIFIED DRIVER OF THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK (ACTION#2).  PALM DECIDED TO CONTACT NEARBY CUSTOMER AND ASK THEM TO HELP WITH COMMUNICATION AND ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE CUSTOMER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE WITH MSDS (ACTION#3).  FIRE DEPT PERSONNEL APPROVED CUSTOMER'S PERSONNEL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND TRANSPORT TRUCK TO THEIR FACILITY.  THE MATERIAL ON STREET AND IN TRAILER WAS ABSORBED AND TRANSFERRED TO OVERPACK DRUM.  REVIEWING THE PICTURES, AFTER THE CLEAN UP THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT ON THE STREET.  THE DAMAGED DRUM OF MICCROLLOY R WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK FOR REMOVAL AND DISPOSAL.  WITH FIRE DEPT APPROVAL THE TRUCK PROCEEDED TO CUSTOMER LOCATION FOR UNLOADING AND FURTHER CLEAN OUT.  THE SPILL MATERIAL IS WITH CUSTOMER WAITING FOR DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

column168: ON 11/03/04, A TRANSFORMER WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING ON AN ONYX TRAILER WHILE OTHER ITEMS WERE BEING OFFLOADED AT AN ONYX TSDF FACILITY IN MENOMONEE FALLS, WI AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 PM.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRANSFORMER WAS LEAKING THROUGH THE TOP COVER SEAL.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS OVERPACKED AND THE METAL FLOOR OF THE TRUCK WAS DECONNED USING DIESEL FUEL. THE DEBRIS GENERATED DURING THE CLEAN UP WAS PLACED INTO THE 55 GALLON DRUM THAT THE TRANSFORMER WAS OVERPACKED INTO.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS INSPECTED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT AND NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED BUT APPARENTLY THE TOP OF THE TRANSFORMER WAS NOT SEALED PROPERLY.  IN THE FUTURE, TRANSFORMER VALVES AND FITTINGS WILL BE INSPECTED FOR LEAKS AND TIGHTNESS PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: VEHICLE WAS HEADING EAST ON I-94 WHEN HE NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM HIS VAN TRAILER.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO SHOULDER OF ROAD.  HE EXAMINED VEHICLE AND NOTED THAT A DRUM HAD TIPPED OVER.  HE IMMEDIATELY (12:45EST) CALLED DISPATCH WHO CALLED CHEMTREC, SPILL CENTER AND STATE POLICE.  TAPLAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE IS ABOUT AN HOUR.  TAPLAN SECURED LEAKING CONTAINER, PLACED IN OVERPACK, CONTAINED LEAKING LIQUID ON ROAD AND SMALL AREA SURROUNDING SPILL.  THE SOIL WAS REMEDIATED, PLACED IN DRUMS AND SENT TO ENVIRITE OF ILLINOIS FOR TREATMENT.  DRIVER WAS ABLE TO LEAVE SCENE BY 2:00 PM.  DRIVER WILL BE RETRAINED ON PRE-TRIP INSPECTION TO MAKE CERTAIN THAT ALL CONTAINERS ARE BLOCKED CORRECTLY ON TRAILER IN FUTURE.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER SITE TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE. HE HOOKED UP AND CHECKED THE LEVEL GAUGE ON THE TANK TO CONFIRM THERE WAS SUFFICIENT ROOM IN THE TANK FOR THE DELIVERY.  HE BEGAN UNLOADING, AND HAD TRANSFERRED ^75% OF HIS LOAD, WHEN A CONTRACT WORKER, WHO HAD BEEN IN THE AREA, CAME OVER, GESTURING TOWARDS THE TOP OF THE TANK.  DRIVER SAW A SPURT OF LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK, AND SOME LIQUID FLOWING DOWN THE WALL OF THE TANK.  HE SHUT OFF HIS PUMP, COMPRESSOR AND CUSTOMER'S VALVE, STOPPING THE FLOW TO THE TANK.  THE CONTRACT WORKER HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT AND WAS RINSED OFF IN A SAFETY SHOWER, CHECKED BY ON-SITE MEDICAL PERSONNEL AND CLEARED.  ALL THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN A DIKE UNDER THE TANK.  THERE WERE NO OFF-SITE COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, AND NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE.  APPROXIMATELY 350 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WERE ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT DPC HOOKED TO CUSTOMER OWNED DPC TRAILER, WHICH WAS PRE-LOADED.  PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, INCLUDED CHECKING THE WING NUTS ON THE 10" DOME LID.  LEFT DPC, WHEN PULLING AWAY FROM THE STOP LIGHT (TURNING LEFT FROM US 61 ONTO US 67), NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO THE SHOULDER.  DPC EMPLOYEE JEFF WAS WITH OUR DRIVER.  JEFF TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT THIS WAS THE FIRST LOAD ON THIS TRAILER AFTER A LINING INSPECTION.  THE FAILURE WAS AT THE RING OF STUDS/NUTS SECURING THE 20" MANWAY.  THE 20" MANWAY IS SECURED WITH STANDARD NUTS, NOT WING NUTS.  OUR DRIVER STATED THAT THE STUDS WERE ALL IN PLACE, BUT APPARENTLY THE NUTS WERE NOT TIGHTENED.  THE DOME IS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THIS TRAILER.  JASON WISDOM--PLANT MANAGER FOR DPC--WENT TO THE SCENE.  WISDOM ESTIMATES THAT THERE WAS 5-10 GALLONS MAX SPILLED ON THE HIGHWAY.  THE RQ FOR THIS MATERIAL IS 100 GALLONS.  DPC MECHANIC TIGHTENED THE NUTS ON THE 20" LID, AND CLEANED UP THE LIQUID WITH OIL DRY.  OUR DRIVER WAS DIRECTED TO RETURN TO THE DPC PLANT TO RINSE OFF THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON COUNTY ROAD F32, 8 MILES EAST OF WESTPHALIA, THE TERRA EXPRESS, INC. VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A VEHICLE ROLL-OVER DAMAGING A VALVE ON THE VEHICLE.  A SPILL RESULTED IN EXCESS OF ONE HUNDRED POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT, WHICH AFFECTED A DRY CREEK BED AND THE PICAYUNE CREEK.  THE WOODBINE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE WOODBINE FIRE DEPARTMENT BUILT A DIRT DAM TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER MIGRATION OF FREE PRODUCT INTO PICAYUNE CREEK.  THE WOODBINE FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED APPROXIMATELY 8,000 GALLONS OF WATER TO THE IMPACTED AREA.  TERRA EXPRESS, INC. CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. OF OMAHA, NEBRASKA, HYDRO-KLEAN, INC. OD DES MOINES, IOWA AND S & S PUMPING SERVICES OF BLAIR, NEBRASKA TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC., HYDRO-KLEAN, INC. AND S & S PUMPING  USED VACUUM TRUCKS TO REMOVE THE IMPACTED WATER FROM THE AFFECTED CREEK.  THERE WERE THREE EXPOSURES AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.  THE TERRA EXPRESS, INC. DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT SIOUX VALLEY HOSPITAL IN MISSOURI, IOWA.  TWO LOCAL FIREMEN WERE ALSO TREATED FOR EXPOSURE AND RELEASED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column168: AT 1812 HOURS ON SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 13TH TANK CAR GATX58194 WAS REPORTED WITH SLOSH TYPE LEAK FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S BENNETT YARD.  ORIGINALLY, CONDUCTOR COREY MORRIS WAS CONCERNED THAT HE MAY HAVE COME IN CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  THE CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND HEALTH WAS CONTACTED AND SPOKE WITH THE EMPLOYEE REDUCING HIS ANXIETY.  NO MEDICAL TREATMENT WAS REQUESTED BY TRAINMAN MORRIS.  SWS WAS CONTACTED TO INSPECT THE RAIL CAR AND PROPERLY SECURE IT FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.  SWS REPRESENTATIVES FOUND TWO (2) OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS/NUTS LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT AND SIX (6) OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS/NUTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  ALL BOLTS/NUTS WERE TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH AS REQUIRED AND THE RAIL CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED FOR ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION ON SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 14TH.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE INSPECTING A TRACK OF RAIL CARS, A TRAIN CREW OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF TANK CAR UTLX 500159.  THE TRAIN CREW NOTIFIED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AND ISOLATED THE AREA.  THE CARRIER NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CALLED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. A CSXT MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDED AND MET WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  BOTH CSXT AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE SUBJECT CAR AND FOUND THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED AND WAS DRIPPING FROM THE MOUNTING FLANGE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  SPECIFICALLY, THE LEAK WAS ORIGINATING FROM ONE OF THE "ALLEN BOLTS" THAT SECURE THE VALVE FLANGE TO THE TANK SHELL.  A CONTAINMENT POOL WAS PLACED UNDERNEATH THE LEAKING FLANGE UNTIL IT COULD BE REPAIRED.  THE PRODUCT SHIPPER/PRODUCER WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE SITUATION.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT A RAILCAR REPAIR COMPANY WOULD BE CALLED TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE LEAKING FLANGE.  THE RAILCAR REPAIR FIRM ARRIVED WITHIN TWO HOURS, AND WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE FLANGE MOUNTING BOLTS SUFFICIENTLY TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO THE DESTINATION TERMINAL (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE AWAY) FOR NORMAL OFFLOADING.  THE CAR WILL BE SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION/REPAIR OF THE VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE AND GASKET.

GATX 44739, LOAD METHANOL, WAS REPORTED TO SPLASH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN CUMBERLAND, MD.  THE SHIPPER, ENOCO WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S MECHANICAL GENERAL FOREMAN INSPECTED THE CAR AND REPORTED THAT PRODUCT HAD SPLASHED OUT FROM AROUND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  ENOCO WAS ADVISED OF THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  THE CONTACTED RESCAR, A MOBILE RAILCAR REPAIR COMPANY, TO RESPOND TO REPAIR THE CAR.  RESCAR RESPONDED ON 11-19-04.  THEY FOUND THAT ONE OF THE SAFETY SWING BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER WAS NOT CORRECTLY APPLIED WHICH LEFT A GAP BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER AND THE TANK NOZZLE PROHIBITING THE MANWAY COVER FROM FORMING A LIQUID TIGHT SEAL.  THEY REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AS PRECAUTION EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO SIGN OF ANY DAMAGE OR WATER AND PROPERLY SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.

column168: 4 PALLETS OF PRODUCT STAGED ON DOCK.  TOO HEAVY TO LOAD INTO NOSE OF EMPTY TRAILER.  WHEN LOADING CREW CAME TO POSITION THAT PALLETS COULD BE LOADED IN A TRAILER, DRIVER FRED PORTER DISCOVERED A SMALL PYRAMID MOUND OF BLUE MATERIAL UNDER THE EDGE OF ONE PALLET.  THERE WAS NO TRAIL OF POWDER LEADING TO WHERE THE PALLETS WERE STAGED.  EXAMINATION OF THE HOLE REVEALED A SMALL TEAR IN THE PAPER BAG AT THE END OF AN OLD INDENTATION.  THE BAG WAS ON THE BOTTOM ROW OF THE PALLET.  THE DAMAGE WAS NOT A CLEAN PUNCTURE LIKE A FORKLIFT WOUND.  THE INDENTATION WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 INCHES LONG BY 1/2 INCH DEEP, WITH A CIRCULAR SHAPE.  LIKE A DOWEL OR ROUND OBJECT HAD BEEN PRESSED INTO THE BAG, WITH THE POWDER INSIDE THE BAG ASSUMING THE SHAPE.  THE SMALL TEAR WAS AT THE DEEPEST END OF THE INDENTATION.  IT WAS OLD DAMAGE THAT WEAKENED BY TRAVEL IN A BOUNCY TRAILER.  I ISOLATED THE SCENE.  THEN CALLED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER AND WAS INFORMED THAT WE COULD PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  I THEN CALLED THE REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERVISOR FOR INSTRUCTIONS.  WE REMOVED THE ONE TORN BAG AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  SWEPT UP THE SMALL AMOUNT THAT WAS ON THE FLOOR AND POURED IT INTO A PLASTIC BAG.  PLACING IT INTO THE SAME RECOVERY DRUM. WILL CONTACT SHIPPER IN THE NEAR FUTURE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY AT PPG INDUSTRIES ON PITTSBURGH ROAD IN CIRCLEVILLE, OHIO, A RELEASE WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TANK TRUCK.  APPARENTLY, THE CUSTOMER HAD PULLED A SAMPLE OF PRODUCT PRIOR TO PRODUCT TRANSFER, AND NEGLECTED TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVE BEFORE TRANSFER BEGAN.  RELEASE WAS DETECTED IMMEDIATELY, AND VALVE WAS SHUT FOR REMAINDER OF TRANSFER.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF RESIN SOLUTION WERE RELEASED TO THE CONCRETE SURFACE.  PPG INDUSTRIES APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS TO THE AFFECTED SURFACE AND NEUTRALIZED THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, AND AN MSDS WAS OBTAINED, PPG INDUSTRIES WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL/DISPOSITION OF THE WASTE GENERATED DURING CLEANUP, PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED.

column168: ON 11-25-2004 AT 0630 HRS, CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAIN Q53624, WAS TRAVELING THROUGH MILAN, TN AT 49 MPH WHEN 3 LOCOMOTIVES AND 13 CARS DERAILED INCLUDING, 7 LOADS OF PLASTIC, 2 LOADS OF GRAIN, 1 LOAD OF PAPER, 2 EMPTIES AND 1 LOADED TANK CAR, GATX 5644, LOAD CARBON DISULFIDE.  THE GATX 5644 WAS TURNED OVER IN AN ADJACENT DITCH.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE CAR.  ENGINE CSXT8100 SUSTAINED A RUPTURED FUEL TANK AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL ONTO THE GROUND.  LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  BECAUSE OF THE GATX5644, THE GIBSON COUNTY EMA INITIATED A PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION OF THE IMMEDIATE AREA WHICH AFFECTED 5 HOMES AND 10 PEOPLE.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED CONTRACTORS TO THE SCENE TO EVALUATE THE DAMAGES TO THE GATX 5644 AND TO REMEDIATE THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL.  THE CONTRACTOR CONFIRMED THAT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE FROM GATX5644.  DUE TO DAMAGES TO THE GATX5644, THE LADING WAS TRANSLOADED TO A GATX5643.  THE GATX5644 WILL BE LOADED ON A FLAT CAR TO BE SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

ON NOVEMBER 22, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 00:10 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR GATX 17179, CONTAINING CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. 8, UN1760, PG II, WAS REPORTED EMITTING A STRONG ODOR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE LATANIER, LA, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) RAIL YARD.  A SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND FOUND A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET.  THE SHIPPER REPLACED THE GASKET, SECURED THE MANWAY COVER, AND CLEANED UP RELEASED LADING FROM THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

column168: IN THE AM OF 11/24/04, A WORKER JUST FINISHED FILLING ONE OF OUR TRUCK MOUNTED SMALL BULK TANKS FROM OUR LARGE BULK TANK OF LIQUID OXYGEN.  THE WORKER FAILED TO DISCONNECT THE FILL LINE AND PROCEEDED TO BACK THE VEHICLE OFF THE FILL PAD.  AS HE BACKED UP THE CONNECTED LINE SNAPPED OFF THE FILL/WITHDRAW PLUMBING ABOUT 18" FROM WHERE IT EXITS THE TANK RESULTING IN THE EMPTYING OF IT'S CONTENTS.  THE WORKER TURNED OFF VEHICLE & NOTIFIED THE Q.C OFFICER WHO QUARANTINED THE AREA.  CONTENTS EMPTIED IN 5 MINUTES AND DISPERSED INTO AIR.  VEHICLE WAS THEN MANUALLY PUSHED BACK AWAY FROM FILL PAD SO AS TO ALLOW TO DESATURATE OF OXYGEN (2 HRS) BEFORE TURNING IGNITION ON.  EMPLOYEE REC'D QUARTER SIZE, MINOR CRYOGENIC BURN ON LEFT FOREARM THAT REQUIRED NO MEDICAL ATTENTION.  EMPLOYEE WAS DISCIPLINED FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW CEMP'S AND RECEIVED RE-TRAINING.  TANK WAS REPAIRED AND TESTED/CERTIFIED BY AN AUTHORIZED AND LICENSED FACILITY.  THERE WAS NO THREAT OR HARM TO ENVIRONMENT NOR SURROUNDING NEIGHBORHOOD.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 22, 2004, CAREFREE CARTAGE, INC. ("CAREFREE") DELIVERED INTERMODAL CONTAINER NUMBER KLTU1138768 TO THE CHICAGOLAND QUAD CITIES EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL ("CHICAGOLAND") LOCATED AT 7715 S. 78TH AVENUE IN BRIDGEVIEW, ILLINOIS 60455.  THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER CONTAINED 80 DRUMS OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN.  THE CONTAINER IS RED, APPROXIMATELY 20 FEET IN LENGTH AND 12 FEET IN HEIGHT, IS OWNED BY "K" LINE, AND IS IDENTIFIED BY THE FOLLOWING NUMBER: KLTU1138768.  UPON RECEIPT, THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND A LEAK OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN WAS DISCOVERED.  SET ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. ("SET") AN ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, WAS RETAINED BY CAREFREE TO INITIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE EFFORTS AT THE CHICAGOLAND FACILITY.  WEARING LEVEL B PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, SET REMOVED ALL OF THE 80 DRUMS FROM THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER.  EACH OF THE DRUMS WERE INSPECTED FOR DAMAGE AND DENTS.  TWENTY-FOUR DRUMS WERE NOT DAMAGED OR DENTED.  FIFTY-FIVE OF THE DRUMS WERE DENTED AND/OR DAMAGED.  THESE DENTED/DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK CONTAINERS.  SET IDENTIFIED ONE DRUM THAT HAD A PINHOLE LEAK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  SET ESTIMATED THAT 18 GALLONS OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN WERE RELEASED FROM THE LEAKING DRUM.  MUCH OF THE EPICHLOROHYDRIN LEAKED INTO THE WOODEN FLOOR BOARDS SERVING AS THE FLOOR OF THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN LEAKED OUTSIDE OF THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER ONTO THE CHASSIS SUPPORTING THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER. APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN LEAKED OUTSIDE OF THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER ONTO A PAVED SURFACE.  SET ENVIRONMENTAL IS IN THE PROCESS OF DECONTAMINATING THE CHASSIS AND REMOVING THE WOODEN FLOOR OF THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER FOR APPROPRIATE HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL.  SUBSEQUENT TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE LEAKING DRUM, CAREFREE COMPLETED AN INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE WHEN THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER SUFFERED THE DAMAGE THAT LED TO THE LEAKING DRUM.  THROUGH ITS INVESTIGATION, CAREFREE BELIEVES THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER WAS DROPPED AND DAMAGED WHEN IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SHIP IN TACOMA, WASHINGTON.  CAREFREE'S INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER, OWNED BY "K" LINE, WAS REPORTED TO BE IN A DAMAGED CONDITION ON OR ABOUT NOVEMBER 6, 2004.  THIS INFORMATION WAS DOCUMENTED IN A "K" LINE UNUSUAL OCCURRENCE REPORT (UOR).  THIS UOR CONFIRMS THAT THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER AND ITS CONTENTS SUSTAINED SERIOUS DAMAGE BEFORE THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER CAME INTO THE POSSESSION OF CAREFREE FOR DELIVERY TO CHICAGOLAND. ALTHOUGH CAREFREE HAS TAKEN THE INITIATIVE TO QUICKLY REMEDIATE THE CONTAMINATION CAUSED BY THE LEAKING DRUM OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN, OUR INVESTIGATION HAS SHOWN THAT IT WAS NOT CAREFREE THAT CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER OR THE DRUM OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN.  NONETHELESS, THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND DRUMS CAUSED THE FOLLOWING DAMAGES: THE EMERGENCY CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION OF PROPERTY AT CHICAGOLAND, THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER WHICH STORED THE DRUMS, THE CHASSIS WHICH SUPPORTED THE INTERMODAL CONTAI

column168: THE YARD MASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN NORTH BERGEN, NJ REPORTED THAT TANK CAR TILX 20130, LOAD OF CARBON DIOXIDE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, WAS VENTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP OF THE DOME AND WAS MAKING A LOUD ROARING SOUND.  THE LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THEY ISOLATED THE IMMEDIATE AREA HAVING ALL EMPLOYEES WORKING OUTSIDE TO GO INDOORS.  THE SHIPPER, BOC GASES, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. BASED ON INFORMATION PROVIDED FROM THE SCENE AND IN CONFERENCE WITH REPRESENTATIVES OF BOC GASES, IT WAS CONCLUDED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT JUST VENTING.  IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THE FRAGIBLE DISK HAD RUPTURED AND DUMPED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR.  BOC GASES DISPATCHED A SERVICE TECHNICIAN TO THE YARD TO INSPECT THE CAR AND TALK WITH LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR CONFIRMED THAT THE FRAGIBLE DISK WAS RUPTURED AND ALL THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR HAD BEEN RELIEVED.  BOC GASES HAD TO OVER NIGHT A REPLACEMENT DISK TO THEIR ALLENTOWN FACILITY AND A BOC TECHNICIAN INSTALLED THE NEW FRAGIBLE DISK ON 12-01.

DRIVER WENT TO TURN AROUND GOT TOO CLOSE TO EDGE OF DRIVE AREA, TRAILER ROLLED INTO DITCH, RELEASE OCCURRED AT THIS TIME.  LOCAL MANAGER CALLED STATE AUTHORITIES, CRUDE OIL CAME OUT FROM VENT LINE.  NO INJURIES, NO EVAC, NO ROAD CLOSURES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: AMINE, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S.
column168: DRIVER UNLOADING WHEN CUSTOMER FILL LINE STARTED LEAKING.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND GOING TO ANOTHER TANK IF REPAIRS CANNOT BE MADE CUSTOMER CLEANED UP.
MISCOMMUNICATION DRIVER THOUGHT THE CONSIGNEE WAS READY TO UNLOAD, BUT THEY WERE CHANGING A FILTER AND WHEN DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT CAME OUT FILTER.  PRODUCT WENT INTO CONTAINED AREA.
DRIVER CLEARING LINES AND LAST SURGE OF AIR CAUSED PRODUCT TO COME OUT VENT.  CUSTOMER CLEANED UP.
DRIVER OVERFILLED TANK
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHEN UNLOADED BY CONSIGNEE.  TWO INNER BOTTLES WERE LEAKING FROM LOOSE LIDS.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

DURING DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE/WAREHOUSE, THE RECEIVER DISCOVERED LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR UNDER A PALLET.  THE PALLET CONTAINS FOUR MINI PORTAFEEDS BANDED TOGETHER ON IT.  PRODUCT IS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THEM.  THERE IS NO PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO IT.  RINCHEM REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO EVERETT GAUTHIER AT NALCO VIA CHEMTREC.  EVERETT RETAINED A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP.  AFTER THE CONTRACTOR HAD SURVEYED THE SITUATION THEY DETERMINED THAT THE PORTAFEED'S VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED.  ALSO, ITS SAFETY CAP WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CONTRACTOR HANDLED ALL ASPECTS OF THE CLEAN UP, INCLUDING THE TRAILER FLOOR.

ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEADING FROM A HOLE CAUSED BY A FORK BLADE WHILE ON THE DOCK.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AND OVERPACK AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WAS NOT ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP NEEDED DUE TO THE EVAPORATION OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT APAC PAPER, THE DRIVER OBSERVED LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY IT AS COMING FROM THE TOP OF A TOTE.  HE FOUND THAT THE TOTE'S FILL CAP WAS LOOSE, ALLOWING MATERIAL TO ESCAPE ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE TIGHTENED THE CAP TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL LOSS.  THE SPILLAGE HAS EVAPORATED AND/OR SOAKED INTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DRIVER WILL CONTINUE WITH HIS DELIVERIES AND OFFER THE SHIPMENT TO ITS CONSIGNEE.

AT THE TIME THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AT THE CONSIGNEE, HE ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR.  HE OBSERVED A DAMP AREA ON THE TRAILER FLOOR UNDER AND AROUND ONE DRUM.  THE CONSIGNEE'S SPILL TEAM RESPONDED AND SURVEYED THE SITUATION.  THEY FOUND AN AREA OF THE BOTTOM CHIME THAT HAD BEEN HIT AND DAMAGED.  IT WAS LEAKING FROM A SMALL HOLE AT THE DAMAGE.  THE SPILL TEAM OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND WIPED UP THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THEY ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF THE LEAK.

DURING DOCK OPERATIONS A FORKLIFT OPERATOR DISCOVERED ONE DRUM DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN HIT BY AN UNKNOWN PASSING FORKLIFT.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THEY SWEPT UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND PUT IT INTO A SEPARATE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINERS WERE PUT INTO OS&D TO AWAIT INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

DOCK SUPERVISOR CALLED TO REPORT THAT ONE DRUM IS LEAKING FROM A DAMAGED AREA NEAR ITS BOTTOM.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN HIT BY A PALLET.  A LOADER HAD PICKED IT UP ON A DRUM PICK AND HAD MOVED IT INTO A TRAILER.  AFTER SETTING IT DOWN HE NOTED AN ODOR.  HE SAW A SMALL PUDDLE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AT THE BASE OF THE DRUM, SO HE REMOVED IT FROM THE TRAILER AND SET IT ON THE DOCK FLOOR.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT OIL DRY ONTO THE SPILL AREAS. HAZMAT INSTRUCTED THEM TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL AND AWAIT THE ARRIVAL OF A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR.  HAZMAT CONTACTED S E T ENVIRONMENTAL FROM WHEELING, ILL. TO RESPOND.  A FIVE HAND CREW FROM S E T ARRIVED AT ABOUT 0850.  THEY PUT THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK THAT WAS PROVIDED BY THE MARKHAM FACILITY.  THEY DECONTAMINATED ALL AFFECTED AREAS OF THE TRAILER AND THE DOCK.  THEY COMPLETED WORK AND DEPARTED AT ABOUT 1030.  BY PRIOR AGREEMENT THEY USED THE FOLLOWING MATERIALS PROVIDED BY JEVIC: ONE 85-GALLON OVERPACK; TWO 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS AND THREE BAGS OF OIL DRY.  ALL DRUMS WERE LEFT AT THE MARKHAM FACILITY, AND PUT INTO OS&D.

THREE DRUMS OF A SHIPMENT HAD BEEN REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE IN MASSACHUSETTS AND WERE BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THEY HAD BEEN REFUSED BECAUSE THE DRUMS WERE DENTED.  ON ARRIVAL AT THE HOUSTON, TX FACILITY, TWO OF THE DRUMS WERE LEAKING FROM CRACKS IN THEIR LOWER ROLLING HOOPS.  DOCK PERSONNEL REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUMS FROM THE SHIPMENT, PUT THEM INTO OVERPACKS AND HELD THEM IN OS&D.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: DURING DELIVERY OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE THE DRIVER FOUND RED MATERIAL DOWN THE SIDE OF ONE DRUM AND ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL HAD DRIED.  THE TOP OF THE DRUM IS DENTED AROUND THE TOP.  IT APPEARS AS IF THE DRUM HAD BEEN HIT DURING LOADING, BREAKING THE SEAL BETWEEN THE HEAD AND THE SIDE.  THE DRIVER BELIEVES THAT NO PRODUCT HAD LEAKED RECENTLY, HOWEVER THE LID HAS NOT RESEALED.  HAZMAT MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR THE DRIVER TO TAKE THE DRUM TO MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL IN CALVERTON, N.Y.  THEY PUT IT INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK.

SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT NORTH OXFORD, MA FACILITY ON THE SHIPPER'S PALLET.  ONE PAIL HAD LEAKED SOME PRODUCT ONTO THE PALLET.  THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK IN PROGRESS, AND THE LEAKAGE HAD DRIED.  THE PAIL WAS GLUED TO THE PALLET. DOCK PERSONNEL REMOVED THE PAIL AND PUT IT INTO OS&D.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS PUT OUT FOR DELIVERY.
RESPONDED TO AREA OF SPILL.  USED THE DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET.  USED PPE & CLEANED UP SPILL ACCORDING TO RESPONSE SHEET.  PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.
RECEIVED A CALL ABOUT CORROSIVE HAZMAT RESPONDED TO CALL WEARING PPE FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.  SPILL CONTAIN TO CARTON RETURNED LEAKER IN A SPILL TUB TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING.
RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE.  FOLLOWED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID.  APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE.  BROUGHT PACKAGE TO CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING THROUGH DMP.

PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN PRIMARY.  ONE 5 LITER PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD A LOOSE CAP. THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

DURING THE OUTBOUND SORT AND LOADING OPERATIONS, IT IS BELIEVED THIS SHIPMENT WAS DROPPED TO THE GROUND CAUSING ONE OF THE INSIDE GLASS BOTTLES TO BREAK.  THE REMAINING FIVE BOTTLES WERE PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

DURING MORNING SORT OPERATIONS THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING A LIQUID WITH A STRONG ODOR.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED WHAT APPEARS TO BE SMALL AMOUNT (18 ML) OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE (MEK) IN A PLASTIC TUBE, SHIPPED IN A FEDEX ENVELOPE.  THE ENVELOPE WAS NOT MARKED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS.  SHIPMENT WAS BEING HELD FOR INVESTIGATION.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY, THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER AND LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE AS A TOTE OF SULFURIC ACID.  HE REPORTS THAT THE TOTE IS EQUIPPED WITH A MANWAY COVER AND THAT THE MANWAY COVER APPEARS TO HAVE COME OFF. THAT HAS ALLOWED SOME OF THE TOTE'S CONTENTS TO SLOSH OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST DETERMINED THAT THE PROPER MITIGATION OF THE SPILL WOULD REQUIRE THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR, AND RETAINED ONE.  THE CONTRACTOR'S CREW ARRIVED AND MADE ENTRY.  THE INSPECTED THE I B C AND DETERMINED THAT IT HAD A LARGE CRACK NEAR ITS TOP. THE MATERIAL MUST BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER I B C.  THE FACILITY'S ENVIRONMENTAL DIRECTOR WAS ABLE TO PROVIDE ONE.  HOWEVER, THE CONTRACTOR DID NOT HAVE A PUMP WITH THEM TO MAKE THE TRANSFER.  SINCE THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAKAGE TAKING PLACE AT THE TIME AND THE CONTAINER WAS ADEQUATELY SECURED, THE FACILITY MANAGER AND THE CONTRACTOR AGREED THAT THE TRANSFER COULD TAKE PLACE ON THE NEXT DAY.  ON THE NEXT MORNING THE CONTRACTOR RETURNED TO THE SITE AND COMPLETED TRANSFERRING THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO THE REPLACEMENT ONE.  AFTER THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED, THE SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THEY DECLINED TO ACCEPT ANY OF IT, BELIEVING THE PACKAGES TO BE CONTAMINATED WITH SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER TOOK THE ENTIRE LOAD TO THE CARRIER'S LOCAL FACILITY.
column172: Composite, with plastic receptacle for liquids and steel outer packaging

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: A FORK LIFT WAS TRANSPORTING A PALLET OF FREIGHT ACROSS THE CARRIER'S DOCK. IT STRUCK AND PUNCTURED ONE DRUM OF H/M.  DOCK PERSONNEL TURNED THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE TO STOP THE ESCAPE OF CONTENTS, THEN PUT THE DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THEY SOLIDIFIED THE SPILLAGE WITH OIL DRY, THEN PACKAGED IT FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN THE SALVAGE DRUM.

AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, THE SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN A DEN IN A ROLLING HOOP.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN HIT BY THE CORNER OF A PALLET.  THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED IT.  THE DRIVER SECURED IT FROM LEAKING AND RETURNED IT TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. FACILITY DOCK PERSONNEL OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND HELD IT PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

DURING UNLOADING OF THE INBOUND PICK UP TRAILER THE UNLOADER FOUND ONE DRUM LEAKING.  IT APPEARS TO BE A PACKAGING DEFECT.  CARRIER'S DOCK PERSONNEL PUT IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD IT FOR INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

DURING STRIPPING OF AN INBOUND, THE UNLOADER FOUND ONE CARTON CRUSHED AND LEAKING.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN JAMMED IN DURING LOADING.  DOCK PERSONNEL REMOVED IT FROM THE SHIPMENT, SET IT IN A DISPOSAL CONTAINER AND PUT IT IN OS&D.  THEY PICKED UP THE SPILLAGE WITH OIL DRY.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AS THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD PRIOR TO LEAVING THE DROP YARD, HE FOUND A TOTE LEAKING.  THE TOTE'S MANWAY COVER HAD COME OFF AND WAS LYING OFF TO ONE SIDE OF THE TOP.  THE DRIVER REPLACED AND RESECURED THE COVER.  HE PURCHASED TWO BAGS OF OIL DRY AND A BUNDLE OF RAGS TO CLEAN THE SPILLAGE UP.  ONCE DONE HE CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THEY ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT CLEAR.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE BROOK PARK, OH FACILITY ONE TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  THE TOTE HAD A CRACKED VALVE.  JEVIC HAZMAT (JHM) NOTIFIED HENKEL THAT THEY HAD A POSSIBLE PACKAGE FAILURE.  HENKEL (ERIC LINSTROM 586-759-5556) TOLD JEVIC TO DISPATCH A CREW AND PROVIDE FULL DETAILS. JEVIC CONTACTED HAZMAT ONE (HMO) TO DISPATCH A CLEAN UP CREW.  UPON ARRIVAL HMO TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE INTO DRUMS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PACKED INTO A DRUM.  FULL PICTURES WERE TAKEN.  J. DIXON NOTIFIED DONITA LACEY (HENKEL) AND INQUIRED AS TO WHERE THE TOTE SHOULD BE RETURNED TO.  D LACEY AUTHORIZED THE TOTE TO BE RETURNED TO THE WARREN, MI PLANT.  PHOTOS OF THE DAMAGED TOTE WERE SENT TO D. LACEY.  JHM IS FOLLOWING UP WITH D. LCEY ON SUBROGATION COST.  SEE SUBROGATION FILE FOR FULL DETAIL.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED ON THE BOX.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE CONTAINER(S) HAD LOOSE CAP(S) AND LEAKED. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE CAP(S) WERE SECURED.  THE CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  THE UNDAMAGED PORTION OF THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

column168: THE ACE TRANSPORT TANKER WAS OFF-LOADING GASOLINE TO ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANKS AT THE DESTINATION.  DURING OFF-LOADING, ONE ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFILLED, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF PETROLEUM.  THE PETROLEUM WAS INITIALLY RELEASED TO A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE; HOWEVER, THE CONTAINMENT FAILED TO SUCCESSFULLY CONTAIN THE RELEASE, AND THE PETROLEUM WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND SURFACE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINMENT.  INCIDENT REPORTED TO NRC.  ACE TRANSPORT DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED TO USE CAVE WHEN OFF-LOADING TO PREVENT OVERFILLS.  THE DESTINATION OWNER (TRADE MART) HAS BEEN ADVISED TO CORRECT PROBLEMS WITH THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE.

AT APPROX. 0900 THE TRAILER STARTED OVERFLOWING SPILLING 469 GALS OF PGO ONTO CONCRETE CONTAINMENT, THEN TO COLLECTION UNIT.  ALL PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED & SENT TO HMS ENV TECH. UNIT.  DURATION OF OVERFLOW WAS APPROX. 90 SEC.  HMS PROCEDURES ON LOADING/UNLOADING PGO REVIEWED W/DRIVER.  A FLEET BULLETIN WAS ISSUED TO ALL HMS DRIVERS EXPLAINING INCIDENT & WARNING THEM TO DOUBLE-CHECK LOAD # ENTERED INTO METER & TO WATCH METER SO IT CAN BE MANUALLY STOPPED IF IT FAILS TO STOP. A WARNING LETTER WAS ISSUED TO THE DRIVER IN THIS INCIDENT.

TWENTY FOOT INTERMODAL CONTAINER LOADED WITH FOURTEEN, DOUBLE STACKED (7 EACH LAYER) TOTES (300 GALLON CAPACITY). TOTES HAD METAL FRAMING CAGES. NO PLYWOOD OR SEPARATOR USED BETWEEN LAYERS. ONE OF THE TOP LAYER TOTES LEAKED. THE LEAKING TOTE HAD CRUSHING DAMAGE AT THE BOTTOM. APPROX 20 GALLONS RELEASED. FLAT CAR AND IMPACTED AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. REMAINING PAINT IN LEAKING TOTE TRANSFERRED INTO NEW TOTE. ALL TOTES WERE RELOADED BACK INTO INTERMODAL UNIT AND PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING TECHNIQUES EMPLOYED TO SECURE THE LOAD. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED, INCIDENT #11022004083. RAIL SHIPPER ALIANCA/HAMBURG SUD, ACTUAL SHIPPER-VALSPAR.

BILL LARSEN, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A SMELL OF ROTTEN CABBAGE COMING FROM TANKCAR GATX 68651 ON TRAIN EBTOI 07 AT THE LIVONIA YARD NEAR MILE POST 114.05 OF THE LIVONIA SUBDIVISION.  MR. LARSEN ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS INSPECTED AND NO LEAK WAS FOUND.  MR. LARSEN REQUESTED A MANAGER OF FIELD OPERATIONS INSPECT THE TANKCAR BEFORE IT WAS PLACED IN THE HUMP YARD.  FRANK LERCH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, AND THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF FIELD OPERATIONS, WERE NOTIFIED.  MR. ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE LIVONIA RAILYARD.  AT 05:49 AM, ROBINSON REQUESTED STATE AND PARISH NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE.  TERRALINE, POINTE COUPEE PARISH SHERIFF'S DISPATCHER, WAS NOTIFIED.  TRACY, DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY, HAZMAT HOTLINE AND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, WERE NOTIFIED. TRACY ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER 04-07-859 TO THE INCIDENT.  TRACY STATED THE REPORT NUMBER WILL MEET BOTH NOTIFICATION REQUIREMENTS FOR THE STATE OF LOUISIANA.  AT 08:23 AM, ROBINSON REPORTED TWO OF THE SIX MANWAY COVER PLATE BOLTS WERE LOOSE CAUSING THE ODOR.  MR. ROBINSON STATED THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED.  MR. ROBINSON STATED THERE WERE A COUPLE OF DROPS OF PRODUCT ON THE TANKCAR, BUT NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.

CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, DON SNOW WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF LEAKING TANK CAR, GATX 3413, IN TRACK 130 IN ROSEVILLE, CA.  AFTER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE OF THE GAUGING DEVICE.  ALL 12 BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED. column168: KEN EGLAND, FOREMAN GENERAL, REPORTED CONTAINER CAR XOMX 340014 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT IN BUTLER YARD 1, TRACK 507 IN MILWAUKEE, WI.  MR EGLAND STATED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET PORT AND WAS LEAKING AT THE RATE OF A DROP EVERY THIRTY SECONDS.  MARK MADAY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 11:48 AM, MGR MADAY REPORTED THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM A LOOSE PACKING RETAINER ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  HE TIGHTENED THE VALVE WITH A CRESCENT WRENCH AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

THE DRIVER CLAIMS THAT WHEN HE WAS COMPLETING THE DELIVERY A SPILL OCCURRED.  HE WAS FILLING A 275 GALLON HEATING OIL TANK WHEN THE VENT STARTED TO OVERPRESSURIZE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED.  THERE WAS NO RUN OFF INTO ANY STORM DRAINS, MDE WAS CONTACTED.

column168: FEDEX ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE COMMERCIAL INVOICE INDICATED "FUEL SAMPLE - NOT REGULATED".  SINCE FEDEX DID NOT HAVE A FLIGHT TO THE US FROM THE ORIGIN, WE INTERLINED IT WITH LAN CHILE AIRLINES.  WHEN THE FREIGHT ARRIVED IN MIAMI, FEDEX TOOK CHARGE OF THE FREIGHT ONCE AGAIN. AS WE WERE PREPARING TO LOAD IT ON A TRUCK FOR DELIVERY WE FOUND THE PACKAGE TO BE LEAKING.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  IN FACT, WE WERE LED TO BELIEVE BY THE SHIPPER, THAT IT WAS NOT REGULATED. THE FAA IN MIAMI WAS NOTIFIED.  I SPOKE TO FAA SA SHERRIE ELLIOTT.  THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

DRIVER PULLED ONTO THE FUEL ISLAND, AND THE TRAILER STARTED DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE SKIN OF THE TANK. TOM DISPATCHER FROM THE GEISMAR TERMINAL GOING TO THE SCENE TO HELP AND IF ANY EQUIPMENT IS NEEDED. column168: 1. CONDUCTOR WAS WALKING DOING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION WHEN HE NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TANK GATX 64059 AT THIS TIME HE CALLED THE YARD OFFICE TO REPORT THE PROBLEM HE HAD FOUND.  THE YARD SUPERVISOR INVESTIGATED THE SITUATION AND NOTICED THE TANK CAR WAS VENTING LP GAS, AT THIS TIME A CALL WAS PLACED TO CHIEF DISPATCH IN BILLERICA MA AND THE EMERGENCY CALL PROCEDURE WAS PUT IN PLACE.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THERE HAZMAT TEAM WERE CALLED IN CONJUNCTION WITH GUILFORD RAIL SYSTEM PERSONNEL.  2045HRS. FIRE DEPARTMENT AT THE SCENE WITH RAILROAD PERSONNEL.  SEVERAL CALLS WERE MADE TO SHIPPER TO SEND A RESPONSE TEAM TO RECTIFY THE SITUATION THEY COULD NOT FIND ANYONE TO COME OUT TO THE SCENE.  SEAL WAS ON THE CAR BUT NOT IN THE CORRECT POSITION TO SECURE LOCKING PIN.  SECTION OF THE YARD WAS CLOSED TO FREIGHT TRAIN OPERATIONS, BUT PASSENGER SERVICE WAS NOT STOPPED. EVENTUALLY THE SHIPPER OFFERED THE FIRE DEPARTMENTS HAZMAT TEAM INFORMATION ON HOW TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND WITH THE HELP OF GUILFORD RAIL SYSTEM SAFETY DEPARTMENT WITH KNOWLEDGE OF TANK CAR FITTINGS, AT THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TIGHTENED UP THE LIQUID LINE DIP TUBE PACKING NUT THAT WAS LOOSE THE REPAIR WAS MADE AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AROUND 0030HRS.  THE NEXT DAY PAUL N. BOGAN (SEA-3 REPRESENTATIVE AND ALSO CHAIRMAN OF THE NEW ENGLAND PROPANE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMITTEE) WENT TO THE SITE TO INSPECT TANK CAR FOR SHIPMENT.  NTSB REFERRAL NUMBER 742286, CHEMTREC REFERRAL NUMBER 11232004082.  2. column168: SHIPMENT OF FIVE DRUMS WERE NOT SECURED PROPERLY IN TRAILER AND SHIFTED AS A RESULT OF TRAILER MOVEMENT.  TWO DRUMS FELL OVER IN THE TRAILER, ONE OF THEM STRIKING AN ALUMINUM DOCK PLATE THAT WAS FOR DELIVERY TO ANOTHER CONSIGNEE.  ONE OF THE DRUMS PUNCTURED CAUSING A SPILL.  THE DRIVER HERSHEL FOUNTAIN, DISCOVERED THE SPILL.  THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID REACTED WITH THE ALUMINUM DOCK PLATE AND PRODUCED A NOXIOUS SMOKE.  BRIAN INHALED SOME OF THE FUMES AND BECAME SICK TO HIS STOMACH.  EVERGREEN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO THE SCENE, AS WAS THE JEFFERSONTOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT.  BETWEEN THE TWO AGENCIES THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  HERSHEL FOUNTAIN WAS EVALUATED BY A PARAMEDIC WHO SUGGESTED THAT HE BE EVALUATED AT THE HOSPITAL.  HERSHEL REFUSED TREATMENT, BUT WAS LATER TAKEN TO BE CHECKED OUT AT CONCENTRA MEDICAL.  HERSHEL WAS RELEASED AND RETURNED THE NEXT MORNING TO BE RELEASED TO WORK.  HE WAS RELEASED BACK TO FULL DUTY AT WORK ON 11-03-04.  QUALITY COUNTS SUPERVISOR KIRBY BILSLAND WAS ALSO ON THE SCENE AFTER THE SPILL.  THE RECOVERY DRUMS USED TO CONTAIN THE MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO CCX DOCK IN LOUISVILLE.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE BOTH NOTIFIED AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 6, 2004, UP'S COUNCIL BLUFFS, IA YARD MASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR TGAX 131016 WAS LEAKING PHOSPHORIC ACID AT A RATE OF FIVE GALLONS PER MINUTE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKCAR.  LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  BECAUSE OF THE NATURE OF THE SPILL, BOTH THE STATE OF IOWA AND DEQ AND THE NRC WERE NOTIFIED. THE START OF THE RELEASE WAS IDENTIFIED AS APPROXIMATELY EIGHT MILES EAST OF BLAIRSTOWN, IOWA.  APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF ACID WAS RELEASED BETWEEN BLAIRSTOWN AND THE COUNCIL BLUFFS YARD AND AN ADDITIONAL 2000 GALLONS WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND IN COUNCIL BLUFFS YARD.  APPROXIMATELY 8700 GALLONS WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE DAMAGED TANK CAR TO A CLEAN TANK CAR AND RETURNED TO PCS FOR REPROCESSING.  A HI-RAIL VACUUM TRUCK EQUIPPED WITH A SPRAY BAR AND A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION WAS APPLIED TO THE CONTAMINATED TRACKS BETWEEN COUNCIL BLUFFS, IOWA AND EIGHT MILES EAST OF BLAIRSTOWN, IOWA.  THE FREE PRODUCT WAS VACUUMED OFF THE GROUND IN COUNCIL BLUFFS YARD, AND RESIDUAL ACID IN THE SOIL WAS NEUTRALIZED.  THE RELEASE APPEARS TO BE FROM HOLES CORRODED IN THE TANK CAR.  THE ACID EVENTUALLY LEAKED OUT OF THE JACKET AND WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND.  INVESTIGATION OF THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE LEAK WILL OCCUR OVER THE NEXT MONTH WHEN THE JACKET IS REMOVED AND THE TANK CAR IS DECONTAMINATED.

MATT, MANAGER INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED CONTAINER APLU906367, EXPERIENCED A LEAK OF MIXED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE LATHROP INTERMODAL RAILYARD IN FRENCH CAMP, CA.  THE CONTAINER WAS REPORTED AS BEING THE TOP CONTAINER ON A STACKED LOAD.  ONE TO TWO GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TOP OF THE BOTTOM CONTAINER IDENTIFIED AT PATU440080.  JAMES MILLERS, SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ALL REGULATORY AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 4:55 AM, JAMES MILLERS, SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT REPORTED THE LEAKING CEASED.  HE ADVISED THE MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE TOP OF CONTAINER PATU440080.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED PORTION, AT THE NORTH END, OF THE RAILYARD.  AGENT MILLERS STATED NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.   MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PERFORMED THE REMEDIATION.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL FOUND TWO 20 GALLON CONTAINERS LEAKING.  THE CAUSE WAS IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING.

column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY PUC INSPECTOR REEVES REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE CITY OF INDUSTRY YARD. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED TANK CAR GATX 45433 AND OBSERVED A SMALL PRODUCT TRAIL ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR, THAT APPEARED TO HAVE COME FROM THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE.  DEVELOPED THE THE OPERATING HANDLE WAS IN PLACE, BUT WHEN INVERTED AND USED TO TURN THE ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET, THE OPERATING HANDLE WAS TURNED 3 FULL TURNS BEFORE PROPERLY SECURING THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET DUE TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP BEING PROPERLY SECURED.  THE PACKING GLAND FOR THE TOP OPERATING VALVE WAS ALSO LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  THE PACKING GLAND WAS LOOSE ENOUGH TO ALLOW PRODUCT TO BYPASS AND DRIBBLE ONTO THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE IT WAS IN TRANSIT.  THE LEFT AND RIGHT SIDE PLACARDS WERE ALSO NOTED TO BE MISSING AND WERE REPLACED.  THE SHIPPER, ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE DISCREPANCIES.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

JOHN STEWART, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED, AND RESPONDED. RMCC EXECUTED STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATORY NOTIFICATIONS.  AT 03:30 PM, MGR. STEWART REPORTED THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE FAILED CAUSING THE RELEASE OF THE LIQUID.  THE TANKCAR WAS TEMPORARILY REPAIRED, THE LEAK STOPPED, AND UP SEAL 9598 PLACED ON THE CAR.  MR. STEWART REQUESTED CHEMTREC CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR RESPONSE AND VALVE REPLACEMENT.

KEITH NORRIS, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED THE ABOVE TANK CAR AS LEAKING IN THE YARD IN ODESSA, TX.  M KELLY MGR. CTS ADVISED THAT INSPECTION OF THE ABOVE CAR REVEALED THAT THREE OF THE SIX MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE NOT APPLIED AND THAT THE OTHER THREE BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT FROM UNDER THE MANWAY COVER.  THE CAR STILL HAD THE SHIPPERS SEAL INTACT.  THE SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS THEN ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.
